$$\boxed{\text{Paper Summary:}  
The paper proposes a Semi-supervised Reward framework (SemiReward) that predicts reward scores to evaluate and filter out high-quality pseudo labels in semi-supervised learning (SSL). The rewarder network is designed to model correlations and predict credible reward scores, which is trained online in a two-stage pipeline assisted by a generator network to avoid confirmation bias. The proposed approach is general, pluggable, and can be used with various SSL methods in wide task types and scenarios. Experimental results demonstrate consistent performance gains and convergence speedup when applying SemiReward to popular SSL algorithms.}

$$\boxed{\text{Strengths:}  
1. The proposed approach is general and pluggable, making it suitable for various SSL methods and task types.
2. The use of a two-stage training pipeline and a generator network helps to avoid confirmation bias and improves the quality of pseudo labels.
3. The rewarder network is designed to model correlations and predict credible reward scores, making it a reliable indicator for high-quality labels.
4. The approach has been extensively evaluated on diverse classification and regression datasets, demonstrating consistent performance gains and convergence speedup.}

$$\boxed{\text{Weaknesses:}  
1. The defined reward scores and rewarder only support sample-level labels, which may not be suitable for fine-grained labels in some scenarios.
2. The approach requires repeating the teacher model and the rewarder several times to get reliable pseudo labels, which may lead to extra computational costs and performance decreasing at the end of training.
3. The approach may not be suitable for imbalanced regression datasets, as it may not be able to select high-quality pseudo labels effectively.}

$$\boxed{\text{Suggestions for Improvement:}  
1. Design a more efficient sampling and selection pipeline for SSL training to reduce computational costs.
2. Explore the use of fine-grained labels in the rewarder network to improve its performance on tasks requiring token-level rewarding.
3. Investigate the use of adaptive data augmentations to further enhance SSL performance.}

$$\boxed{\text{Recommendation:}  
Based on the experimental results and the proposed approach, I recommend that the authors continue to improve and refine the SemiReward framework. The approach has shown promising results and has the potential to become a new paradigm for measuring pseudo-label quality in SSL scenarios. However, further research is needed to address the limitations and weaknesses identified in the paper.}$

